Name: Aloo pie
Description: This soft and fried pastry is a variant of the samosa, made from flour and water, and filled with boiled, spiced and mashed potatoes and other vegetables like green peas. Its shape is similar to a calzone, and it is usually larger than a samosa, approximately 5 inches (13 cm) long.[1]

Name: Apple crispApple crumble
Description: A dessert consisting of baked apples topped with a crispy crust. Many different kinds of fruit can substituted for apples, and one of the most common variants is 'apple rhubarb crisp' including rhubarb. It is a simpler alternative to apple pie and apple cobbler.

Name: Apple pie
Description: A fruit pie (or tart) in which the principal filling ingredient is crisp and acidic cooking apples such as the Bramley or Granny Smith

Name: Australian and New Zealand meat pie
Description: A hand-sized meat pie containing largely minced meat and gravy sometimes with onion and often consumed as a takeaway food snack. The pie itself is congruent with the United Kingdom's steak pie.

Name: Bacon and egg pie
Description: A pie containing bacon, egg and often onion

Name: Bakewell tart
Description: A tart with a shortcrust pastry shell, spread with jam and filled with a sponge-like, ground almond filling.[3] Often covered with nuts, such as almonds and peanuts, a top layer of almond flavored icing, and a half glacé cherry.

Name: Banana cream pie
Description: A cream pie made with a rich custard made from milk, cream, flour, and eggs and combined with sliced bananas in a pastry or graham crumb crust. It is often made with a whipped cream topping.

Name: Banoffee pie
Description: An English pastry-based dessert made from bananas,[4] toffee[4] and cream, either on a pastry base or digestive biscuit crumb crust.

Name: Bay tat
Description: A sweet pie or tart made from coconut milk with pineapple jam or coconut jam as filling.

Name: Bavarian Cream Pie
Description: A sweet chocolatey pie best served cold, topped with Bavarian cream.

Name: Bean pie
Description: A sweet custard pie with a filling of mashed beans, sugar, butter, milk, and spices, including vanilla, cinnamon, and nutmeg.

Name: Bedfordshire clanger
Description: An elongated, suet crust pie with a savory filling at one end (meat, potatoes and vegetables) and a sweet filling (jam or fruit) at the other.

Name: Bisteeyapastilla, etc.
Description: A traditional Berber meat pie traditionally made of squab (fledgling pigeons) in crisp layers of warka dough, with a crunchy layer of toasted and ground almonds, cinnamon, and sugar.  Many variant transliterations: bastilla, bsteeya, b'stilla, bstilla, ...

Name: Blackberry pie
Description: A fruit pie with a filling made from blackberries.

Name: Black bottom pie
Description: A layer of chocolate pastry cream or pudding, the "black bottom," topped with whipped cream or meringue in a crust of variable composition.

Name: Black bun
Description: A pastry-covered fruitcake, traditionally eaten on Twelfth Night.

Name: Blueberry pie
Description: A fruit pie (or tart) in which the principal filling ingredient is blueberries.

Name: Bob Andy pie
Description: A sweet custard pie, spiced with cinnamon and cloves.

Name: Bougatsa
Description: Consists of custard, cheese, or minced meat filling between layers of phyllo.

Name: Boysenberry pie
Description: Made with boysenberries, often simmered into a softer sweeter "preserve"-type gel, most frequently with a second covering crust, either lattice or with only a few cutouts.

Name: Bridie
Description: A small, savory pie filled with minced steak, butter, and beef suet seasoned with salt and pepper. Sometimes with an addition of minced onions.

Name: Buko pie
Description: A sweet pie originating from the Philippines. It was only available to the island country, until a method of freezing was used. It is a very popular pie, consisting of young coconuts.

Name: Bumbleberry pie
Description: This is a sweet fruit pie in which the filling consists of blackberries, blueberries, raspberries and strawberries.[5]  Other varieties also include other berries or the addition of grapes.  The color of the filling is a deep purple, and it is baked in a typical pie shell pâte sucrée.

Name: Bundevara
Description: An elongated, strudel-like pie filled with sweetened pumpkin.

Name: Bündner Nusstorte
Description: A traditional sweet, caramelised nut-filled pastry (generally walnut).

Name: Burek
Description: Phyllo filled with cheese, meat, potatoes and other vegetables. Found in the cuisines of the Balkans, the Caucasus, Central Asia, West Asia, and parts of North Africa.

Name: Butter pie
Description: Made with sliced potatoes, onion, butter, salt and pepper in a light pastry casing.

Name: Butter tart
Description: Butter, sugar and eggs in a pastry shell, with raisins, pecans or walnuts often added.

Name: Buttermilk pie
Description: A traditional custard-like pie in a pastry crust with a filling made of a mixture of sugar, butter, eggs, buttermilk and flour.

Name: Canelé
Description: A small French pastry with a soft and tender custard center and a dark, thick caramelized crust.

Name: Cantaloupe pie
Description: A custard pie of cantaloupe, butter, eggs, and nutmeg, with meringue topping.

Name: Caramel tart
Description: A sweet tart, filled with soft piped caramel. Sometimes topped with whipped cream or drizzled with chocolate.

Name: Cashew pie
Description: Prepared using cashews as a main ingredient.

Name: Cheesecake
Description: Cream cheese and pastry; may come in a variety of flavors.

Name: Cheese pie
Description: A pie with a filling similar to cheesecake with a graham wafer crust and often topped with fruit.

Name: Cherry pie
Description: A pie baked with a cherry filling. Usually made with tart rather than sweet cherries so as to control the sweetness of the pie.

Name: Chess pie
Description: A custard pie with a filling composed of eggs, butter, granulated sugar, brown sugar, vanilla and corn meal.

Name: Chestnut pie
Description: A pie prepared using chestnuts as a primary ingredient

Name: Chicken and mushroom pie
Description: A pie made with a pastry crust with a filling of small pieces of chicken and sliced mushrooms in a creamy sauce.

Name: Chiffon pie
Description: A pie with a filling made by folding meringue or whipped cream into a mixture resembling a fruit curd (most commonly lemon) in a crust of variable composition.  Can also be made with canned pumpkin in place of the fruit.

Name: Chinese piePâté chinois
Description: A layered French Canadian dish similar to the British cottage pie. It is made with ground beef and sautéed onions on the bottom layer, canned corn (whole-kernel or creamed) for the middle layer, and mashed potatoes on top.

Name: Cobbler
Description: A dish consisting of a fruit or savory filling poured into a large baking dish and covered with a batter, biscuit, or dumpling before being baked.

Name: Coconut cream pie
Description: A cream pie made with a rich custard made from milk, cream, flour, eggs, and shredded coconut in a pastry or graham crumb crust, usually topped with whipped cream and toasted coconut.

Name: Cookie Cake Pie
Description: A combination of cookie dough and cake batter baked together in a pie crust.

Name: Corned beef pie
Description: A pie with a filling of corned beef, onion and other vegetables such as corn, peas or carrot. The pie can be made with a mashed potato topping, as in cottage pie, or with a traditional pastry crust.

Name: Coulibiac
Description: A baked pie with a filling made with salmon or sturgeon,[6] rice, hard-boiled eggs, mushrooms, and dill.

Name: Cumberland pie
Description: A meat pie topped with a crust of bread crumbs.

Name: Curry pie
Description: A pie with a pastry crust filled with Indian or Chinese curry.

Name: Curry puff
Description: A small pie consisting of curry with chicken and potatoes in a deep-fried or baked pastry shell, similar to an empanada.

Name: Custard tartflans pâtissier
Description: A baked pastry consisting of an pastry crust filled with egg custard. French custard tarts are generally shallower and larger than British ones, and therefore served in slices rather than as individual items.

Name: Derby pie
Description: A chocolate and walnut pie with a pastry dough crust; commonly made with pecans, chocolate chips and Kentucky bourbon.

Name: Egg pie
Description: A sweet Filipino pie with an egg custard filling and a characteristic toasty brown top made from egg whites.

Name: Egg tart
Description: A baked pastry consisting of egg custard in a cookie crust or puff crust.

Name: Empanada
Description: A stuffed pastry, baked or fried and stuffed with a variety of fillings, including meat, cheese, vegetables or fruit. Popular throughout Spain, Portugal, Latin America, Central America, the Philippines, Indonesia, Malaysia, and the Caribbean.

Name: Fish pieFisherman's Pie
Description: A dish made with white fish in a béchamel sauce with a mashed potato topping, similar to cottage pie.

Name: Flan
Description: An open pastry or sponge cake containing a sweet or savory filling.

Name: Flan chino [es]
Description: A rectangular-shaped egg dessert similar to a cross between a flan and a tocinillo de cielo.

Name: Flapper pie
Description: A custard pie with a graham wafer crust, topped with meringue.

Name: Fleischkuekle
Description: A fried meat pie made with flat bread. A traditional Volga German dish, through immigration became an addition to the cuisine of North Dakota.

Name: Flipper pie
Description: A meat pie made from young harp seal flippers.

Name: Fried pie
Description: A small, fried pastry crust pie containing a fruit filling.

Name: Gibanica
Description: A traditional Balkan pastry, usually made with white cheese (feta, sirene).

Name: Green grape pie
Description: A pie traditionally made with wild green grapes before seeds have formed in the spring, such as early May.

Name: Homity pie
Description: A traditional British, open vegetable pie. The pastry crust contains a filling of potatoes and an onion and leek mixture, which is then covered with cheese.

Name: Hornazo
Description: A Spanish meat pie made with flour and yeast and stuffed with pork loin, spicy chorizo sausage and hard-boiled eggs.

Name: Indian potato pie
Description: A spiced potato and sweet potato pie baked in a crust created from multiple layers of Filo pastry.

Name: Jamaican patty
Description: A small, baked pastry coloured yellow with turmeric, usually filled with seasoned ground beef and with Scotch Bonnet pepper added for spice.

Name: Kalakukko
Description: A loaf of bread filled with fish.

Name: Karelian pasties
Description: Pasties made from a thin rye crust usually with a filling of rice, but originally the filling used to be mashed potatoes or barley.

Name: Key lime pie
Description: A pie made with key lime juice, egg yolks, and sweetened condensed milk in a crust.

Name: Khachapuri
Description: A cheese-filled bread dish.

Name: Killie pie
Description: A steak pie served at Kilmarnock F.C. football ground.

Name: Knish
Description: Baked or fried dumpling made of flaky dough with filling of mashed potatoes, ground meat, sauerkraut, onions, kasha or cheese.

Name: Kuchen
Description: The generic term referring to "cake" in German.

Name: Kurnik
Description: A dome-shaped savory Russian pirog, usually filled with chicken or turkey, eggs, onions, kasha or rice, and other optional components.

Name: Lanttusupikas
Description: A double folded buttered flaky crust pie, filled with thin, braised swede slices and pork loin.[8]

Name: Lemon ice box pie
Description: Lemon juice, eggs, and condensed milk in a pie crust,[9] with preparation very similar to that of key lime pie.

Name: Lemon meringue pie
Description: A shortcrust or shortbread pastry with lemon curd filling and a fluffy meringue topping.

Name: Manchester tart
Description: A baked tart consisting of a shortcrust pastry shell, spread with raspberry jam, covered with a custard filling and topped with flakes of coconut and a Maraschino cherry.

Name: Meat and potato pie
Origin: Yorkshire, Lancashire, and Cumbria regions in the United Kingdom
Description: Potato, either lamb or beef, and sometimes carrot or onion baked in a pastry shell.

Name: Meat pie
Description: A preparation common especially to the UK and Commonwealth countries. Originally a way to stretch ingredients when quantities were not enough for a single meal. Usually made with a hot water crust.

Name: Melktert
Description: A South African dessert consisting of a sweet pastry crust containing a creamy filling made from milk, flour, sugar and eggs.

Name: Melton Mowbray pork pie
Description: A hand-formed crust pork pie made with uncured chopped rather than minced, meat.

Name: Millionaire pie
Description: A no-bake pie with whipped topping, pineapple, coconut and pecans

Name: Mince pie
Description: A small British sweet pie traditionally served during the Christmas season; a sweet pastry case filled with currants, suet and spices. Centuries ago they contained meat, suet and spices.

Name: Mississippi mud pie
Description: Dessert pie consisting of a gooey chocolate filling on top of a crumbly chocolate crust; usually served with ice cream.

Name: Moravian chicken pie
Description: A traditional double crusted pie made with a flaky pastry filled with only chunks of chicken and a thick chicken broth-based sauce. Unlike chicken "pot pies", no vegetables are included in the filling. Served with hot chicken gravy on the side.

Name: Mustard tart
Description: A pie made of puff pastry, Dijon mustard, Emmentaler or Gruyère cheese, sliced tomatoes and sprinkled with spices (herbes de Provence, salt and pepper).

Name: Natchitoches meat pie
Description: Crescent-shaped, flaky wheat pastry turnover with a savory meat filling.

Name: Neenish Tart
Description: A tart made with a pastry base and with icing of two colours on top. The filling consists  of sweet gelatine-set cream, mock cream, icing sugar paste, or a lemon-flavoured filling—most familiar to New Zealand residents—made from butter, icing sugar, sweetened condensed milk and lemon juice. The Australian version of the Pineapple tart is similar but is filled with pineapple jam and topped with passionfruit icing.

Name: ÖçpoçmaqEchpochmak
Description: A triangular pastry, filled with minced beef, onion and potatoes. Considered a Tartar national dish.

Name: Pască
Description: A traditional Easter pie filled with fresh cheese like urdă or cottage cheese. Other variants include sour cream, chocolate, or berries fillings.

Name: Pastafrola
Origin: Río de la Plata (Argentina, Uruguay, Paraguay)
Description: A jam-filled tart with shortcrust pastry lattice. Fillings may include quince cheese, dulce de batata (sweet potato jam), dulce de leche, guava, or strawberry jam.[10]

Name: Pastel de nata
Description: A custard tart made with egg yolk. Also known as pastél de Belém due to their geographic origin.

Name: Pasty
Description: A traditional lunch food for Cornish miners. The claim that the rolled part of the crust was used as a handle and left uneaten where it was soiled with arsenic-laden ore from the miner's hand is a myth.[11] They are also popular in Canada and the Upper Peninsula of Michigan, United States due to Cornish migration.

Name: Peach pie
Description: Prepared with peaches as the primary ingredient, with added spices such as nutmeg, ginger or cinnamon. May be strictly a fruit pie, or a custard based pie. Because peaches are a high moisture fruit and produce copious amounts of juice as they cook, peach pies often have a lattice top to allow steam to vent and prevent excessive liquid build-up during baking, which could result in a runny pie.

Name: Peanut pie
Description: Prepared with peanuts or peanut butter as a primary ingredient.

Name: Pear tart
Description: Typically Parisian, called tarte bourdaloue.

Name: Pecan pie
Description: A pie made primarily of corn syrup or molasses and pecan nuts in a pie shell.

Name: Pie à la mode
Description: A pie with ice cream on top.

Name: Pirog
Description: The generic term for pies and pasties in Eastern-Slavic cuisines. The filling for pirog may be sweet and contain quark or cottage cheese, fruits like apples, plums or various berries, as well as honey, nuts or poppy seeds. Savory versions may consist of meat, fish, mushrooms, cabbage, rice, buckwheat groats or potato.

Name: Pirozhkipirozhok, piroshki
Description: The generic word for individual-sized baked or fried buns (small pirogs) stuffed with a variety of fillings.

Name: Pork pie
Description: A traditional British meat pie consisting of roughly chopped pork and pork jelly sealed in a hot water crust pastry.

Name: Pot pie
Description: A savory pie made from pastry crust, usually served in individual containers. Normally made of a creamy sauce, turkey or chicken meat, carrots, peas, and pearl onions.  This dish is sometimes served with rice.

Name: Pumpkin pie
Description: A pumpkin-based custard flavored with nutmeg, cinnamon, cloves, and ginger, baked in a single pie shell. Sometimes the crust is a graham cracker crust or a pastry dough crust. Very common in the autumn and early winter holidays.

Name: Quiche
Description: The generic term; pastry base and sides, with various chopped fillings set in an egg/milk mix.

Name: Qumeshtore me pete
Description: A pie filled with apricots, plums, and honey.

Name: Raisin pie
Description: A pie in which the main ingredient is raisins.

Name: Rappie pie
Description: An Acadian dish, also known as râpure, consisting of grated potatoes, meat, onions, and soup stock.

Name: Raspberry pie
Description: A pie filled with raspberries, sometimes topped with whipped cream.

Name: Rhubarb pie
Description: A pie filled with diced rhubarb.

Name: Samosasingara, sambusac, samsa
Origin: Indian Subcontinent, Central Asia, Western Asia, Horn of Africa, North Africa, South Africa
Description: A fried or baked pastry with a savory filling such as spiced potatoes, onions, peas, lentils, ground lamb or chicken, often accompanied by chutney.

Name: Saskatoonberry pie
Description: A pie filled with saskatoonberries.

Name: Sausage roll
Description: A long cylindrical roll of sausagemeat encased in flaky or puff pastry.

Name: Scotch pie
Description: A small, double-crust meat pie filled with minced mutton or other meat.

Name: Sea-pieCipaille
Description: A layered meat pie made with meat or fish, and is known to have been served to British sailors during the 18th century.

Name: Sfiha
Description: An open-faced meat pie made with ground mutton.

Name: Shaker lemon pie
Description: Thinly sliced lemons, sugar, and eggs in a crust, first made by the Shakers.

Name: Shepherd's Pie
Description: A roasted mutton or lamb cooked in pie dish lined with mashed potatoes, with a mashed potato crust on top.

Name: Shoofly pie
Description: A molasses pie common to Pennsylvania and the Delaware Valley.

Name: Soparnik
Description: A pie with a filling of chard, chives (or young onion leaves), parsley, olive oil and garlic.

Name: Southern tomato pie
Description: A savory dish consisting of a pie shell with a filling of tomatoes (sometimes with basil or other herbs), covered with a topping of grated cheese mixed with either mayonnaise or a white sauce.[12][13]

Name: Spanakopitaspinach pie
Description: A pie with a filling of chopped spinach, feta cheese, onions and eggs.

Name: Stargazy pie
Description: A Cornish dish made of baked pilchards, along with eggs and potatoes, covered with a pastry crust; the fish heads (and sometimes tails) are baked protruding through the crust, thus appearing to be gazing skyward.

Name: Steak and kidney pie
Description: A pie filled with a mixture of diced beef, diced kidney (often of ox, lamb, or pork), fried onion, and brown gravy.

Name: Steak pie
Description: A meat pie made from stewing steak and beef gravy, enclosed in a pastry shell.

Name: Strawberry pie
Description: A pie filled with strawberries, sometimes topped with whipped cream.

Name: Strawberry rhubarb pie
Description: A pie filled with strawberries and rhubarb, usually with a lattice-style crust on top.

Name: Sugar cream pie
Description: A single-crust pie with a filling made from flour, butter, salt, vanilla, and cream, with brown sugar or maple syrup

Name: Sweet potato pie[14]
Description: A large tart in an open pie shell without a top crust, with a filling consisting of mashed sweet potatoes, milk, sugar and eggs, flavored with spices such as nutmeg.

Name: Tamale pie
Description: A meat pie with a cornmeal crust and typical Mexican tamale fillings arranged in several layers. The meat is traditionally ground beef.

Name: Tarta capuchina [es]
Description: A pie or cake made mainly with egg yolk and syrup. The pie or "cake" is usually presented in a cylindrical or rectangle shape, depending on the mold.

Name: Tarta de Santiago
Description: A cake or pie with a filling of ground almonds, eggs and sugar. The top of the pie is usually decorated with powdered sugar, masked by an imprint of the Cross of Saint James (cruz de Santiago) which gives the pastry its name.

Name: Tarte conversation
Description: A tart made with puff pastry that is filled with a frangipane cream and topped with royal icing.

Name: TiropitaGreek cheese pie
Description: A pie made with layers of buttered filo (alternatively, thick pastry or puff-pastry) and filled with a cheese-egg mixture.

Name: Tocinillo de cielo [es]
Description: A dessert made from yolk egg and caramelized sugar that is compact and bright yellow. The tradition places its origin in Jerez de la Frontera more than 500 years ago.

Name: Tourtière
Description: A meat pie[15] originating from Quebec, usually made with finely diced pork, veal, beef, fish, or wild game.

Name: Treacle tart
Description: A shortcrust pastry with a thick filling of golden syrup, breadcrumbs, and lemon juice.

Name: Vlaai
Description: A pie or tart consisting of a pastry and a filling of either fruit, a crumbled butter and sugar mix, or a cooked rice and custard porridge.

Name: Västerbotten pie
Description: A pie filled with a mixture of Västerbotten cheese, cream and eggs.

Name: Walnut pie
Description: A pie prepared using walnuts as a main ingredient.

Name: Watalappam
Description: A coconut custard pudding made of coconut milk or condensed milk, jaggery, cashew nuts, eggs, and various spices, including cardamom, cloves, and nutmeg.

Name: Wähe[16]
Description: A flat pie or cake prepared with short pastry and a topping of either fruits, vegetables, or cheese.

Name: Woolton pie[17]
Description: A pie filled with vegetables such as potatoes or parsnips, cauliflower, swede, carrots, and turnips, topped with potato pastry, grated cheese, and served with vegetable gravy.

Name: Whoopie pie
Description: An American baked product that may be considered either a cookie, pie or cake. It is made of two round mound-shaped pieces of chocolate cake, or sometimes pumpkin or gingerbread cake, with a sweet, creamy filling or frosting sandwiched between them.

Name: Zelnik
Description: A pastry composed of thin layers of filo dough filled with combinations of sirene, eggs, spinach, sorrel, browned meat, leeks, rice, and brined cabbage.
